[1] Coconut mite, red palm weevil - India (Goa)
Date: Mon 12 Apr 2010
Source: The Navhind Times [edited]
<http://www.navhindtimes.in/news/pests-disease-eat-coconut-yield-bicholim>


Pests eat into coconut yield in Bicholim
----------------------------------------
The considerable drop of about 40-50 per cent of coconut yield this year
[2010] in Bicholim [subdistrict] have become a matter of deep concern to
agriculturists and coconut growers. Zonal agriculture officer Pradeep Malik
said the major factor that has affected yield is mite attack, which leads
to hardening of the outer cover, reduces the size of a coconut, and affects
the pulp inside. He said potash fertilisers have proved to be effective to
fight mite attack.

About 2500 hectares [approx 6200 acres] of land is under coconut
cultivation in Bicholim. The total [average] coconut yield was about 200
000 nuts which may fall this year [2010], Mr Malik said.

The coconut trees are also attacked by red palm weevils, locally called
'ronto'. However, the use of thymate, oiled karanj cake, and oiled neem
cake can keep the ronto off the coconut plants, Mr Malik observed. If the
coconut plants are infested by ronto, the plant dies slowly as ronto
attacks inside the stem of a palm and cannot be detected at an early stage.

[byline: Ramesh Savaikar]

